			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">vibratoPattern:<br />&nbsp; .byte 2, 3, 3, 3, 2, 0, -2, -3, -3, -3, -2, 0<br /></div><br /><br />Today I figured out how to make a musically consistent yet computationally efficient vibrato control.<br /><br />Vibrato adds a sinusoid to the note period. FamiTracker's vibrato is typical of tracker vibrato, which makes the depth constant in period units. This means that for higher pitches, which have lower periods, a given amount of vibrato depth will sound stronger than it does for lower pitches, which have higher periods. But if the change in period for a given vibrato depth setting is proportional to the note's own period, it'll sound the same for low and high pitches.<br /><br />I've also found that looping the vibrato once every 12 frames (roughly equivalent to FamiTracker <a href="http://famitracker.com/wiki/index.php?title=Effect_4xy" class="postlink">effect <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">45y</tt></a> for depth <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">y</tt>) is within normal limits of vibrato on a string or wind instrument.<br /><br />This, however, leaves portamento as an excuse.</div>

					
						<br clear="all" /><br />

